The two governments signed an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents claim that the name change would undermine Macedonia's Slavic majority identity.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has raised doubts as to whether the minimum 50 percent participation required for the referendum to be considered valid will be achieved.
The question on the ballot in the referendum is: "Are you in favour of membership in NATO and the EU with approval of the agreement with Greece?"
But supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, claim that it is worth changing names if it makes Macedonia, one of the countries formed when Yugoslavia split, able to join the EU and NATO.
"I am here to vote for the future of our country, for young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because that means safer lives for all of us," said 79-year-old Olivera Georgievska, in Skopje.
The referendum is not binding, but enough Members of Parliament have said that they intend to follow the results to make it decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority of Parliament.
According to the State Election Commission, no irregularities had been reported at 13:00.
However, the participation was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the recent 2016 parliamentary election, when 66 percent of registered voters voted.
"I vote for my children, we belong in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital Skopje.
Macedonia’s Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko vote in the Macedonian referendum on the country’s name change, which would pave the way for membership of NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia 30 September 2018.
Outside the parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, organized a small stage and venue in front of the tents set up by those who boycott the referendum.
"We are for NATO and the European Union, but we want to go with our heads in the air, not to sneak in through the back door," Kavardarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they don’t welcome us as Macedonia, we can turn to others, such as China and Russia, and become part of a Euro-Asiatic integration.”
According to Prime Minister Zaev, membership of NATO would lead to well-needed investments in Macedonia, which has a unemployment rate of over 20 percent.
“I think the absolute majority will vote yes, because over 80 percent of our citizens are for the EU and NATO,” Zaev said.
He said a "yes" result would be a "confirmation of our future."
