John Edward: Language Skills Decisive for Global Citizens
Scottish independent schools retain outstanding academic achievements and this continued in 2018 with yet another set of outstanding trial results, which is only reinforced by individual and collective progress in sports, arts, music and other societal endeavors.
With up to 30,000 students in Scotland, the schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further education, their chosen careers and their role as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement tailored curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and in demand topics in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
It’s a powerful reminder that we can’t just rely on English when creating relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s trial results show that languages are at the top of the list, with the highest number of approved results in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students studying foreign languages received an A in the Higher Grade final exam.
Data, collected from SCIS 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students who studied Mandarin received an A in Higher Grade, and 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as crucial skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subject choices are now considered as important as natural sciences, engineering, engineering and mathematics on curricula in independent schools and beyond.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Commission for Employment and Skills found that employers had difficulty filling their vacancies for various reasons, with 17 percent being attributed to a lack of language skills.
With that said, language skills become increasingly necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more future jobs requiring language skills, these skills become necessary in a globalized world.
Regardless of your career choice, they will have a real advantage in the future if they have adopted a second language.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a survey of more than 4,000 British adults published by YouGov 2013, 75% said they could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation in it, and where French was the only language that totaled up in a two-digit percentage (15%).
That is why it is so important to invest in language education for our children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those used in developing countries, gives your child a better chance of finding a meaningful job in the future.
In Scotland, each school will learn different combinations of languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach in languages considered most important to the UK by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from within independent schools, with teachers specializing in this field.
Scottish independent schools strive to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and provide them with the skills needed to succeed, regardless of what the future holds for them.
In a global economic environment it is undoubtedly language that continues to be decisive for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for Scottish youth.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
