While Ri reiterated his well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a nuclear-power-shaped approach that would lead to the reward of North Korea when it took gradual steps, his statement appeared significant, as it did not reject a unilateral nuclear solution so far.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim promised to work against "the development of nuclear weapons on the Korean Peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first dismantle its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused negotiations to ease harsh international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘deletion first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its purpose through coercion and even opposes the ‘declaration of ending the war’,” Ri said.
"The notion that sanctions can get us on our knees is a dream for people who lack knowledge of us.
