Ri did not mention plans at a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader highlighted at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korea’s leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the party on this issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea and not the United States, the Korean Peninsula’s nuclear disarmament would not have come to such an end.”
Yet the tone in Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s future ability to reach U.S. mainland with missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but it said that much work remains and that sanctions must remain until North Korea disarms.
